      <mj-text font-size="45px" font-weight="600" line-height="55px">
        Bangladesh Police Extort, Harass Rohingya Refugees
      </mj-text>
      <mj-text color="#666869"  line-height="22px"  font-size="18px"
      padding-bottom="20px">
        Imagine that angry military men burned down your village and 
        forced you to flee your country. You seek shelter in an 
        overcrowded refugee camp across the border and spend years 
        trying to keep your family safe and eke out a living, while 
        threats from armed groups and other dangers mount.
      </mj-text>

      <mj-text color="#666869"  line-height="22px"  font-size="18px"
      padding-bottom="20px">
       Now imagine that the police meant to protect you are instead 
       piling on the abuse.
      </mj-text>

      <mj-text color="#666869"  line-height="22px"  font-size="18px"
      padding-bottom="20px">
       For many <a href="https://www.hrw.org/tag/rohingya" class="link-color">Rohingya</a> living 
       in refugee camps in Cox's Bazaar, 
       <a href="https://www.hrw.org/asia/bangladesh" class="link-color" target="_blank">
       Bangladesh</a>, this is a 
       daily reality. A 
       <a href="https://www.hrw.org/news/2023/01/17/bangladesh-rampant-police-abuse-rohingya-refugees" 
       class="link-color" target="_blank">new report</a> finds that 
       members of Bangladesh's Armed Police Battalion (APBn), which 
       oversees security in the camps, is committing extortion, 
       arbitrary arrests, and harassment of Rohingya refugees.
      </mj-text>

      <mj-text color="#666869"  line-height="22px"  font-size="18px"
      padding-bottom="20px">
       Human Rights Watch spoke to dozens of refugees and reviewed 
       police reports, finding among other abuses several cases of 
       Rohingya being detained on fabricated drug charges or being 
       framed with drugs or weapons.
      </mj-text>

      <mj-text color="#666869" line-height="22px"  font-size="18px"
      padding-bottom="0">
       One man, Sayed Hossein, who works as a health volunteer with an 
       international organization, said police arrested him allegedly for 
       a social media post he made. At the station, they demanded a bribe. 
       When his family could not pay it, he said that officers photographed
      him with drugs, posted the photos to social media, and detained him on
     drug trafficking charges.
      </mj-text>

      <mj-image src="https://i.postimg.cc/dtYfWrTy/women-in-hijab.jpg" 
       alt="woman-in-hijab"
      href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vhfb-ZsMpwg"
      padding-top="0" target="_blank">
      </mj-image>

      <mj-text color="#666869" font-size="13px"line-height="22px" 
      padding-top="0">
        WATCH: No Justice, No Freedom for Rohingya  
      </mj-text>

        <mj-text color="#666869"  line-height="22px" font-size="18px"
      padding-top="0" padding-bottom="20px">
       
      The crackdown has compounded fear among the one million 
      Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh, the majority of whom fled 
      <a href="https://www.hrw.org/asia/myanmar-burma" 
      class="link-color" target="_blank">Myanmar</a> in late 2017 after the country's military onslaught 
      against the Rohingya, which amounted to 
      <a href="https://www.hrw.org/news/2022/08/24/myanmar-no-justice-no-freedom-rohingya-5-years"
       class="link-color" target="_blank">crimes against 
      humanity</a>  and possible genocide. The police abuses have 
      escalated amid <a href="https://www.hrw.org/news/2022/04/04/bangladesh-new-restrictions-rohingya-camps" 
      class="link-color" target="_blank">increasingly coercive restrictions</a> by 
      Bangladesh authorities on refugees' livelihoods, movement, 
      and education in the camps, including 
      <a href="https://www.hrw.org/news/2022/05/11/bangladesh-police-beating-rohingya-refugees" 
      class="link-color" target="_blank">harassment at 
      checkpoints</a>  and 
      <a href="https://www.hrw.org/news/2022/03/21/bangladesh-officials-threaten-rohingya-setting-schools" 
      class="link-color" target="_blank">closing community schools</a> and markets. 
      They also face threats of 
      <a href="https://www.hrw.org/news/2022/03/21/bangladesh-officials-threaten-rohingya-setting-schools" 
      class="link-color" target="_blank">violence</a> from armed gangs in the 
      camps.
      </mj-text>

        <mj-text color="#666869"  line-height="22px" font-size="18px"
      padding-top="0" padding-bottom="20px">
       
      Sadly, the police abuse is now familiar. “In Myanmar, the 
      security forces used to charge us money for anything, any 
      time they wanted,” one man said. “Now in the camps, 
      Bangladesh law enforcement is doing the same thing.”
      </mj-text>

        <mj-text color="#666869"  line-height="22px" font-size="18px"
      padding-top="0" padding-bottom="20px" font-weight="600">
      <a href="https://www.hrw.org/news/2023/01/17/bangladesh-rampant-police-abuse-rohingya-refugees" 
      class="link__color-line" target="_blank"> Read More</a>
      </mj-text>

